Here is a little history lesson on California Pottery:
The heyday of California Pottery was from the 1920's through the 1950's. There were a number of talented artisans producing colorful and dramatic designs in the Southern California area. The 5 best known were Bauer, Pacific, Gladding-McBean, Vernon and Metlox. Smaller, lesser known companies included Batchelder, Catalina Island, Brayton Laguna, La Mirada, Meyers and Winfield just to name a few. Due to the topography of So. Cal., there was no shortage of unique and interesting clay combinations. Mix that with the skill and vision of artisans / craftsmen, in a rapidly growing area, and countless potteries were formed. Today, pottery wares from California are becoming more, and more collectible.

Here is a little history lesson on California Pottery:
The heyday of California Pottery was from the 1920's through the 1950's. There were a number of talented artisans producing colorful and dramatic designs in the Southern California area. The 5 best known were Bauer, Pacific, Gladding-McBean, Vernon and Metlox. Smaller, lesser known companies included Batchelder, Catalina Island, Brayton Laguna, La Mirada, Meyers and Winfield just to name a few. Due to the topography of So. Some fun information I found about the Whitely Exercise Co:
The Whitely name comes from Alex Whitely, who had published works on the subject of exercise, for men and women, dating to 1891 — and perhaps earlier. He is credited with inspiring Joseph Pilates, among others. The earliest Whitely Exercisers appear to have been manufactured by the Independent Electric Company, but a few years later products would be credited to the Whitely Exerciser Company.

In 1897, the Whitely Exerciser Company signed “the father of modern bodybuilding”, the big man who is the little body of the Mr. Olympia trophies, Eugen Sandow as their European agent. Sandow was to to represent the company and demonstrate the product abroad. It was a great success. Perhaps too much so. According to David L. Chapman in Sandow the Magnificent: Eugen Sandow and the Beginnings of Bodybuilding, Sandow did more than take the money and sell:  "Sandow found that this device was so enthusiastically received that a year after he began work for Whitely he quit abruptly and established his own rival business in France. There he produced his particular version of the device and called it: Sandow’s Own Combined Developer.”

Title: Vintage Ni'ihau Kaiki Shell Lei Necklace - 100% Genuine Rice Shell - The Forbidden Island Hawaii - Wedding Lei - Hula Lei - Beautiful!!!
Description:
Vintage 1950s or 1960s Ni'ihau Lei using Kaiki Shells (aka Rice Shells).  Most popular with Hula Dancers and Wedding Leis.

This particular lei has 12 strands and measures 36" total but is meant to be doubled up and tied with the Kukui Nut and grosgrain ribbon.  

These Laiki shells are of high luster and are all of the same approximate size.  The color ranges from white to offwhite with some having very light speckles - all consistent with the finest laiki shell leis/necklaces.

It is easily recognizable as a VINTAGE Lei based on the "Clasp" as this was a popular closure in the 1950s and 1960s.  It was made by the native Ni'ihau family as everything is consistent with all definitions.  

We purchased this piece on the Island of Maui in the locals city of Wailuku in a shop with many amazing estate finds.

Some info about Laiki  shell leis:
"The Laiki shells ("rice shells") tend to be white or yellow in hue and are have the same appearance as a grain of rice. These shells are pierced differently, from end to end, and can be found in the long single strands (Kui Pololei) favored by Hawai'i's queens. Today, you see then in the elaborate wedding leis still used by Ni'ihau brides..." - manandmollusc.net
